  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "Sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) has a greater bond angle than ozone (O\u2083) primarily due to differences in the central atoms and the distribution of lone pair electron density. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n### **1. Central Atom Differences:**\n- **Ozone (O\u2083):**\n  - **Central Atom:** Oxygen\n  - **Electron Configuration:** Oxygen is a second-period element with no available d-orbitals.\n  - **Lone Pairs:** The central oxygen in ozone has lone pairs that are held tightly due to oxygen's high electronegativity and small atomic size.\n\n- **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):**\n  - **Central Atom:** Sulfur\n  - **Electron Configuration:** Sulfur is a third-period element and can utilize d-orbitals (though their role is minimal in bonding for many molecules).\n  - **Lone Pairs:** The central sulfur in SO\u2082 has lone pairs that are more diffuse because sulfur is larger and less electronegative than oxygen.\n\n### **2. Lone Pair Repulsion:**\n- **Localized vs. Diffuse Lone Pairs:**\n  - In O\u2083, the lone pairs on the central oxygen are more localized and exert stronger repulsive forces on the bonding pairs. This increased repulsion compresses the bond angle.\n  - In SO\u2082, the lone pairs on the central sulfur are more diffuse and spread out over a larger volume. This reduces the repulsive force between lone pairs and bonding pairs, allowing the bond angle to be larger.\n\n### **3. Bonding Considerations:**\n- **Bond Order and Resonance:**\n  - Both O\u2083 and SO\u2082 exhibit resonance structures, but the nature of bonding differs slightly. In SO\u2082, the double bonds between sulfur and oxygen can be better stabilized due to sulfur's ability to handle expanded octets, which can also influence bond angles.\n\n### **4. Overall Effect on Bond Angle:**\n- The combination of a larger central atom (sulfur vs. oxygen) and more diffuse lone pairs results in reduced lone pair-bond pair repulsion in SO\u2082 compared to O\u2083. Consequently, SO\u2082 adopts a slightly larger bond angle.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nBecause sulfur\u2019s lone pairs are more spread out than oxygen\u2019s, the lone pair\u2013bond pair repulsions in SO\u2082 are weaker than in ozone. This allows SO\u2082 to adopt a larger bond angle than O\u2083.",
